ce:section.ce:para:
The metal ions, including Co2+, Mg2+, Sn2+, Fe2+, Cu2+, Pb2+, Zn2+, Na+, Fe3+, Ni2+, and Ag+ were used to determine the selectivity of NCDs toward metal ions. These ions are commonly found in living organisms, the environment, foods, medicines, and supplements. It is believed that the fluorescent intensity and wavelength of NCDs can be altered by the addition of metal ions via the photoinduced charge transfer process [32,58–61]. CDs are thus sensitive and selective sensors used for metal ion detection. We found that only Cu2+ could quench the fluorescent intensity of our NCDs by more than 40% (Fig. 5
                        a and b). This may be because the nitrogen-rich NCDs have higher thermodynamic affinity and faster chelating with Cu2+ than with other metal ions [32,58]. In addition, CDs have excellent electron donating ability [52,62]. Therefore, the favorable energy level of d-orbitals of Cu2+ with respect to the lowest unoccupied molecular orbitals of NCDs produces non-radiative photoinduced electron transfer, and consequently fluorescent quenching [63,64]. The fluorescent intensity of the NCDs was found to depend on the Cu2+ concentration (Fig. 5c). The limit of detection (LOD) of Cu2+, calculated from the Stern-Volmer plot using the 3σ convention, was 0.62μM (Fig. 5d), comparable to or better than that in other studies of Cu2+ sensors using CDs (Table 1
                        ). These results demonstrated that NCDs can be used as selective sensors for the determination of sub-micromolar concentrations of Cu2+ ions. We also tested the fluorescent quenching by metal ions of the NCDs on filter paper. The image of the NCD-coated filter paper was taken under UV light after applying the metal ion solutions with H2O as a control. Only the area treated with Cu2+ became dark, demonstrating selective and fast quenching of NCD fluorescence by the Cu2+ ions (Fig. 5e). In addition, the NCD-coated filter paper showed a sensitivity of up to 0.0001M (Fig. 5f). These results demonstrated the potential of our NCDs as paper-based devices for the detection of Cu2+.
